<h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

<p>
    Cloud computing has undergone significant evolution since its inception in the early 2000s. Initially, it primarily focused on providing basic infrastructure services, allowing businesses to rent computing resources on-demand rather than maintaining their own physical servers. This Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) model, pioneered by Amazon Web Services (AWS), revolutionized how companies approached IT infrastructure and paved the way for more flexible and scalable computing solutions.
</p>
<p>
    As the technology matured, cloud providers expanded their offerings to include Platform as a Service (PaaS) and Software as a Service (SaaS) models. PaaS allowed developers to build, run, and manage applications without the complexity of maintaining the underlying infrastructure, while SaaS delivered software applications over the internet, eliminating the need for local installation and management. This evolution democratized access to advanced technologies and tools, enabling businesses of all sizes to leverage sophisticated software solutions without significant upfront investments.
</p>
<p>
    More recently, cloud computing has evolved to encompass edge computing, serverless architectures, and multi-cloud strategies. Edge computing brings data processing closer to the source, reducing latency and improving performance for applications requiring real-time processing. Serverless computing abstracts away server management entirely, allowing developers to focus solely on writing code. Meanwhile, multi-cloud approaches have gained popularity, with organizations leveraging services from multiple providers to optimize performance, cost, and reliability. These advancements continue to shape the cloud landscape, driving innovation and transforming how businesses operate in the digital age.
</p>
